          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Build and cook",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Melt the {{unsalted-butter}} in a small pan over medium heat. Add the {{onion}} and fry for 4 minutes. Add the {{garlic}}, {{ginger-root}}, {{garam-masala}}, {{cumin-ground}}, {{coriander-ground}}, {{chilli-powder}}, and {{tomato-puree}} and stir for 1 minute. Transfer to the slow cooker. Add the {{chicken-thighs-boneless}}, {{tinned-tomatoes}}, and {{sea-salt-fine}}. Cook on low for 6 hours, until the chicken is tender and pulling apart. Stir the {{double-cream}} through at the end. Taste and adjust seasoning.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Remove the lid and cook on high for 20 to 30 minutes to reduce. The sauce should coat the back of a spoon",
              "cause": "Tinned tomatoes released a lot of liquid",
              "symptom": "Sauce too thin and watery"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Stir in another 50 ml double cream and a pinch of caster sugar. Butter at the finish also softens the acidity",
              "cause": "Tinned tomatoes were very acidic, or not enough cream",
              "symptom": "Sauce tastes sour and acidic"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Boneless thighs are the correct cut for slow cooker curries. Breast meat overcooks in 6 hours and becomes stringy. Use thighs",
              "cause": "Breast meat used instead of thighs, or overcooked",
              "symptom": "Chicken dry and stringy"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Butter chicken is the most widely eaten restaurant curry in Britain and one of the most cooked at home. The slow cooker version requires less attention than a stovetop version and produces a deeper-flavoured sauce. Serve with basmati rice and naan, and a small bowl of mango chutney and yoghurt alongside.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
